 &lt;strong>20.1&lt;/strong> Introduction to Computational CFD
 &lt;a class="anchor" href="#201-introduction-to-computational-cfd">#&lt;/a>
&lt;/h1>
&lt;!-- Eric Meier -->
&lt;p>&lt;strong>What is computational fluid dynamics?&lt;/strong> Put simply, it&amp;rsquo;s the use of computers to obtain a numerical solution to the governing equations of fluid dynamics. As always, the numerical solution is an approximation to the real solution to the equations, but additionally those equations are themselves only an approximation of the real physics.&lt;/p>
&lt;p align="center"> &lt;img alt="Figure 20.1" src="https://peppyhare.github.io/r/img/20.1.png" /> &lt;/p>
&lt;p>We will be interested in speeds much less than \( c \) (\( 3 \cdot 10^8 m/s) \) and distances much greater than the atomic radius \( \alpha_{bohr} = 5 \cdot 10^{-11} m \).&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Governing Equations</title><link>https://peppyhare.github.io/r/notes/UWAA543/ch20-2/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://peppyhare.github.io/r/notes/UWAA543/ch20-2/</guid><description>&lt;h1 id="governing-equations">
