 &lt;strong>20.3&lt;/strong> Reduced Models
 &lt;a class="anchor" href="#203-reduced-models">#&lt;/a>
&lt;/h2>
&lt;p>Further simplifications to the fluid models provide equations that are easier to solve. But we have to make sure that the reduced models (anything that&amp;rsquo;s not the full equation system) still capture the relevant physics of the problem.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Let&amp;rsquo;s assume the (2D) flow is&lt;/p>
&lt;ul>
&lt;li>irrotational \( (\curl v = 0) \)&lt;/li>
&lt;li>isentropic&lt;/li>
&lt;li>steady-state&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>
&lt;p>This lets us apply potential flow theory. Since the flow is irrotational, the curl of the velocity field is zero, so we can define a potential&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Equation Types</title><link>https://peppyhare.github.io/r/notes/UWAA543/ch20-4/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://peppyhare.github.io/r/notes/UWAA543/ch20-4/</guid><description>&lt;h1 id="equation-types">
 Equation Types
 &lt;a class="anchor" href="#equation-types">#&lt;/a>
&lt;/h1>
&lt;p>PDE&amp;rsquo;s can be classified as elliptic, parabolic, or hyperbolic. The type of equation will suggest the choice of an appropriate algorithm.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>The equation type can change for different flow parameters, or even for different regions within the same domain.&lt;/p>
